3. Create toy classification dataset using Scikit-Learn's make_moons() function. Visualize it and then build a model to fit it at over 85% accuracy.

What is make_moons()? : It creates a toy dataset of two different coloured 'moons', that are interleaved (aka, data 0 and 1 contaminate/intertwined with the opposite data, adding some complexity to data). A very useful first step to test out a neural network on a binary classification model!

Our goal : As stated on the title, we want to aim for 85% accuracy.

Wow, already 83% accuracy without any substantial layers in our model! Let's see it visually on graph.

But to visualize it, we'll need to form a function named plot_decision_boundary which:

  • Takes X and y data from the trained model.
  • Creates a meshgrid off of X values.
  • Makes predictions across meshgrid.
  • Plots the predictions by drawing a line, separating where the different zones are.
In[78]:
import numpy as np

def plot_decision_boundary(model, X, y):
    """
    Plots the decision boundary created by a model predicting on X.
    This function has been adapted from two phenomenal resources:
    1. CS231n - https://cs231n.github.io/neural-networks-case-study/
    2. Made with ML basics - https://github.com/GokuMohandas/MadeWithML/blob/main/notebooks/08_Neural_Networks.ipynb
    """
    # Define the axis boundaries of the plot and create a meshgrid
    x_min, x_max = X[:, 0].min() - 0.1, X[:, 0].max() + 0.1 # defines the boundaries of the min and max. They have a buffer of 0.1 from the min, and the max of each axis
    y_min, y_max = X[:, 1].min() - 0.1, X[:, 1].max() + 0.1
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(x_min, x_max, 100), # linspace(start, stop, num) generates sequence of values that are evenly spaced from start to stop.
                         np.linspace(y_min, y_max, 100)) # create 100 evenly spaced points for xmin, xmax, ymin, and ymax.
    
    # Create X values (we're going to predict on all of these)
    x_in = np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()] # stack 2D arrays together
    # .ravel > NumPy method that flattens a 2D array into 1D. The stack and flattening, allows the pair of coordinates (x and y) be used more efficiently by ML models.

    # Make predictions using the trained model
    y_pred = model.predict(x_in)

    # Check for multi-class
    if model.output_shape[-1] > 1: # checks the final dimension of the model's output chape, shape bigger than 1 = multi classification
        print('doing multiclass classification...')
        # We have to reshape our predictions to get then ready for plotting
        y_pred = np.argmax(y_pred, axis=1).reshape(xx.shape)
    else:
        print('doing binary classification...')
        y_pred = np.round(np.max(y_pred, axis=1)).reshape(xx.shape)

    # Plot decision boundary
    plt.contourf(xx, yy, y_pred, cmap=plt.cm.RdYlBu, alpha=0.7) # filled contour plot, to show x and y positions on the graph, along with the prediction. set alpha/transparency to 0.7 so we can see underneath overlapped dots
    plt.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, s=40, cmap=plt.cm.RdYlBu) # scatter plot of actual data, with x and y labels.
    plt.xlim(xx.min(), xx.max()) # last two, sets the max and min limits of the range in meshgrid/data
    plt.ylim(yy.min(), yy.max())

5. Recreate TensorFlow's softmax activation function in your own code, and that it can accept/return tensors.

Next step of the agenda, build a ML model for the dataset, and present it visually with its predictions as well!

There's a few changes needed to be made if we were to use the previous model, as the model is binary classification use, rather than multi classification (which is this data problem):

  • Input shape: Our shape is 28 by 28 tensors, (each pixel fits a tensor). We will have to squish it down to one dimensional 784 tensors.

  • Output shape: Will be 10, as we got 10 categories the model has to predict from.

    • Change output activation from sigmoid to softmax. The goal is to predict the likelihood the image is to be a category from 0 to 1. Then the model picks the category thats most likely to be the picture.

  • Loss function: Change the binary loss function to multiclass loss function.

    • Our labels are not one hot encoded, but numerical. So we'll use tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy.

We will also treat the test data as our validation dataset.

But before we do that, we'll have to somehow create our own softmax activation function for this particular exercise. Seems easy on paper as its just probability, but I honestly have zero fuckin clue how to start creating this function.

So what does softmax actually do?: Let's ask Deepseek/ChatGPT

  1. Input: We get an array of raw scores, aka our tensors into softmax [2.0, 1.0, -2.0]
  2. Exponentiation: We apply exponentiation on Euler's number, with the help of the raw scores. So all values stay positive, and further accentuate the values that have higher scores.
    • Exponents - Maximum raw score is donw to ensure numerical stability, and not get values so out of proportion.
    • Euler's number = ~2.718 [e^ 2.0, e^ 1.0, e^ -2.0] = [7.39, 2.71, 0.135] We essentially use Euler's number, and exponentiate it with every raw score.
  3. Normalization: Sum up all values from step 2, then divide it on each exponentiated raw score. This keeps all sum of scores = 1, making them interpretable as probabilities, as they essentially all add up to 100%.
  4. Output: Shat out our probability list for every category in our data.

Let's go ahead and create a function based on what I've just learnt.

In[]:
# create the softmax function on my own

def softmax(logits): # Step 1: Input our array of raw scores
    """Compute softmax from a given array of logits"""
    
    # Step 2: Exponentiate with Euler's number, while subtracting from max value to ensure numerical stability
    max_logits = np.max(logits)
    exp_value = np.exp(logits-max_logits)

    # Step 3: Normalization from dividing the sum of all exponentiated values
    probabilities = exp_value/np.sum(exp_value)

    # Step 4: Output probabilities
    return probabilities

The code above actually doesn't work with our model. Because we are using TensorFlow, it can only implement using Tensor code, but we used NumPy code instead for the softmax function.

Therefore we'll need to overhaul it and fit it with Tensor code instead.

Create softmax function, but its TensorFlow friendly:

In[122]:
# create TensorFlow friendly softmax function

def custom_softmax(logits): # Step 1: Input our array of raw scores
    """Compute softmax from a given array of logits"""
    
    # Step 2: Exponentiate with Euler's number, while subtracting from max value to ensure numerical stability
    max_logits = tf.reduce_max(logits, axis=-1, keepdims=True) # axis=-1 > apply it all the way till the last tensor (to help us find the max value)
    exp_value = tf.exp(logits-max_logits)

    # Step 3: Normalization from dividing the sum of all exponentiated values
    probabilities = exp_value/tf.reduce_sum(exp_value, axis=-1, keepdims=True) # keepdims=True > we need to keep it the same shape to the logits, or else we'll break the model

    # Step 4: Output probabilities
    return probabilities

Let's test out the function

logits = np.array([2.0, 1.0, -2.0])
print(custom_softmax(logits))

# setup multi categorical model for the clothing MNIST data
tf.random.set_seed(35)

# model layers

Finding ideal learning rate of Adam

One thing we could do, is find the ideal learning rate of Adam, our optimizer. We so far don't know what that value is. But we can find it through creating a mathematical operator and function, that allows us to exponentially increase the learning rate of Adam, and then see the historic results through storing it in a variable.

In[129]:
# Create a model that increases learning rate exponentially, and then storing results in a variable
tf.random.set_seed(35)

model_5 = tf.keras.Sequential([
    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28,28)),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(4, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(10),
    tf.keras.layers.Lambda(custom_softmax)
])

model_5.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.SparseCategoricalCrossentropy(),
                optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(),
                metrics=['accuracy'])

# create learning rate scheduler, updating Adam's learning rate constantly
lr_scheduler = tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(lambda epoch: 1e-3 * 10 ** (epoch/20)) # form mathematical operation, for exponential increase in learning rate

find_learningrate = model_5.fit(train_data, train_labels, epochs=40, validation_data=(test_data, test_labels), callbacks=[lr_scheduler])

77%, still not close enough! So let's see what else we could try to further improve accuracy.

I will start by asking for opinions on neural network layers, using deepseek/chatgpt, and randomly implement them one by one.

ChatGPT's opinion:

1. Convolutional Layers: They are much better suited for image data, rather than Dense. What it does is, you can give more specified directions when learning image patterns. filter allows the model to learn features of the image, and kernel_size tells the ML model to scan the image in small patches of an image, to extract local patterns, rather than identifying by every pixel.

Example tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu', padding='same')

2. Pooling layers: Reduces the image size, while still keeping important features of the image. How it does it, is taking an area of pixels, and then finding the one pixel that is most important in keeping the image's feature. This helps reduce small noises in the image, such as dust particles or lighting effects.

Original data:
1   3   2   4  
5   6   7   8  
3   2   9   5  
4   6   1   7  

Turns into:
6   8  
6   9

See how a 2x2 space of number, was picked from it to be kept into the smaller box? (1 3 5 6, with 6 being chosen as deemed the most important feature out of these 4 numbers)

Example tf.keras.layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2))

3. Batch Normalization: This is added after convolutional layers, which can help speed up training. It prevents internal covariate shift, aka when activation layers in a model, change their distribution while training, causing lots of needed readjustments due to unstable activations, making it hard for the network to learn features efficiently. This causes vanishing/exploding gradients, where we see no changes in model learning, or explosive changes during training of neural network.

When added, it stabilizes the activations, allowing for more stable gradients, therefore more consistent outputs for further neural network layers to learn from, improving model performance.

(This explanation took a long time for me to get right lol)

Example: tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization()

Instead of 20 epochs, we'll work with 5 epochs, to save on time and resources when experimenting. We'll be trying out these 3 specific activation layers. By the sounds of it, they are more effective when placed at the front of the ML model sandwich, as they seem to be more of a pre-processing activation function, prepearing the image data for the layers below them.

Our model didn't work! What happened is the input_shape has to be moved onto the first layer for the model to work correctly. Let's try and fix that with (28,28,1). Why the 1? Conv2D expects a 4D input. TensorFlow is happy with a 2D array for input, but Conv2D expects 3D (height, width, channels). The data we work on is black and white, therefore it uses 1 channel, which is why its (28,28,1).

7. Make a function to show an image of a certain class of the fashion MNIST dataset and make a prediction on it.

For example, plot 3 images of the T-shirt class with their predictions.

So we'll create a function, that allows to take the variables: Model, Test_data_images, True_labels, Class_names, Class_category, Number_of_images

In[247]:
# create function to display image of certain class
import random

def plot_class_images(model, images, true_labels, class_names, class_category, num_images):

    # select only the specified class_category
    category_index = class_names.index(class_category) # get index value of class_category
    category_image = images[true_labels == category_index] # only keep the images with the specified category

    # Select random images from the filtered category
    random_indices = np.random.choice(len(category_image), num_images, replace=False)
    selected_images = category_image[random_indices] # select images from the random_indices

    # Reshape images to fit the model input (batch_size, 28, 28, 1)
    selected_images = selected_images.reshape(-1, 28, 28, 1)
    
    # Make predictions
    pred_probs = model.predict(selected_images)
    pred_labels = [class_names[i] for i in pred_probs.argmax(axis=1)]

    # Plot the images with their predictions
    plt.figure(figsize=(num_images * 5, 5))

    for i in range(num_images):
        plt.subplot(1, num_images, i + 1)
        plt.imshow(selected_images[i].reshape(28,28), cmap=plt.cm.binary)
        true_label = class_category
        pred_label = pred_labels[i]
        confidence = 100 * np.max(pred_probs[i])

        # Set title colour based on correctness
        color = 'green' if pred_label == true_label else 'red'

        plt.xlabel(f'Pred: {pred_label} ({confidence:.0f}%)\nTrue: {true_label}', color=color)
        plt.xticks([])
        plt.yticks([])

    plt.show()
